tter devo\ntion to the cause and boundless energy to\nwork, write, and speak in its behalf.\n.Jy he J. own e fforts she ^yept awa y. the\nb ittle cynicism of an age which, sometimes\n?tv'\nsentimentality. She demonstrated that the\nlove which mothw's lavish on their children\nfor their mothers which h'ef dl\u00e9o^n^the\nhearts of sons and daughters of ev^rv aire\nfte wL\u00b0Ln\u00abrf fW\nHer sound conviction that the finest qual\nities entrusted to men ond women\u2014unsel\nfishness love and devotion_are the essen\nfiai\u00ab nf* mnftovQ'InvAmof orv\u00eea\nMofnl\u00fc-t Z, IfXivI\u00ce\nsponse and today Afotnors Day is obsorvod,\never-increasingly, in more than 40 countries,\nWithout benefit of an elaborate organiza\ntion Miss Jarvis showed the wav for millions\n'f,.!L,Zrr,. rTZ f, T,! lie\nwomen to offer proper tribute to\n\u00eenotherhoo\u00ef\u00fcn th^'broadest fens\u00e9 h\nmotnernooa in me Droadest sense.\n\nA good many people seem to believe that\nnext year something resembling the old OPA\nwill be brought back from the dead, and\nprices will immediately drop.\nThis is onp of thoso ilhmiorm that should\ninis iS one Ot tnose Illusions mat Should\nscotched as soon as possible. For, regard\nless of what the law may or may not attempt\nto do, tHfere are certain economic principles\ninvolved which are as inevitable as the move\nment of the planets.\nFirstiOf all, no one will produce anything\nat a loss. We could pass a law, for instance,\nsaying that a dozen eggs shall be sold for\ntwenty-fiye cents, and a good suit of clothes\nsold for twenty dollars. But no farmer would\nproduce those eggs and no manufacturer\nZf \u00c4fmtav wn\u00c4ltaw SimPle reaSOn\nthat bankruptcy would follow.\nSecondly, we cannot make any merchant\nhandle goods at a loss. Today, for instance,\ntypical retail stores, including both the big\nchain systems and many independent stores,\nearn a smaller profit on each dollar of sales\nthan they did under OPA. That profit, gen\nerally, runs from one or two per cent to about\nsix cents on volume of trade, depending on\nthe kind of goods handled. There certainly is\nno room in this field to make any dent m the\nprices paid by the consumer.\nThirdly, price fixing by fiat is the best\nfriend the black market has. It makes for\nscarcity in the legitimate, law-abiding chan\nnels Of trade. And it makes for abundance in\nundercover dealings, where the price charg\ned is all the traffic will bear\u2014right down to\nthe last penny. The racketeer and his custom\ners get the goods\u2014the responsible merchant\nand the masses of people go without.\nToday's prices are the result of record\nwages, enormous government spending, full\n_. ji.iT u j?\nemployment, high taxes, and other such for\nces. Competition keeps them as low as poss\nible. Government meddling would be the\nworst possible way to attack the issue.\nFacts of Life\nbe\nI\nBABSON Discusses Washington\nBABSON PARK, Mass., i\nDecember 3\u2014Everyone is\nasking what Mr. Truman\nand his Democratic Con\ngress will do. This I will\ndiscuss in today's column,\nalthough my conclusions\nwill probably satisfy no\none.\nTRUMAN AND LABOR\nSince the election Wil\nliam Green.sthe able Pres\nthe American\nFederation of Labor, was\nmy guest here at Babson\nPark. There is no doubt\n\nident of\nbut that he feels that Mr.\nTruman owes his victory wholly to the farm-!\ners and the wageworkers. Without doubt the\nTaft-Hartley Law will be modified in several\nways Certainly, employers should have the,\nright to state their case to their wageworkers;\nand moreover should be obliged to take the\nsame anti-communist oath as do the labor\nleaders.\nRoger W. Babson\nIt must not be forgotten that a COALITION,\nat any time, of the Republicans and Southern\nDemocrats could hold up any legislation that\nthe President might greatly desire. This could\napply to UNREASONABLE excess profits\ntaxes, price controls, changes In income brack\nets, New Deal dreams and other legislation\nwhich would be apt to bring about a decline in\ngeneral business. Hence, although there is\nnothing in the Truman victory which could\nhelp business, there is much which could harm\n\nA Good Appointment\nGovernor-elect Elbert N. Carvel has an\nnounced that he will name Harris B. Mc\nDowell, Jr., as his Secretary of State. This\nappointment is a good one. Mr. Carvel and\nMr. McDowell have worked together during\nrecent sessions of\nthe General Assembly, i\nThe Secretary of State will be closer to the\nGovernor than any other State official dur-:\ning his term of office. The two men must;\nwork in harmony and close cooperation in\nhandling the affairs of state. This, because!\nof their past close affiliations, they should be\nable to do. Mr. McDowell has served in both\nthe House of Representatives and the State\nSenate. His knowledge of the workings of\nthese two branches of the legislative body\nshould hav\u00a3 equipped him to work in har-;\nmony with the Representatives and Senators.\nIn going outside the legal profession for a\nSecretary of State we believe that Governor\nCarvel has acted wisely. For several\nyears past a myth has been built Up that no\none but a lawyer could satisfactorily fill the\noffice. This reasoning W6 have always be\ni- _j c* xu\nlieved to be w r rong. Some of the most out\nstanding Secretaries of State during our rec\nollection have been laymen. Mr. McDowell\nwill be given an opportunity to prove the fal\nlacy of this line of reasoning. As Mr. Mc\nDowell assumes the office of Secretary of\nState he will find his administrative abili\nties tested to the limit. The State Corpora\ntion Department, which will come under his\nsupervision, must be administered ably. He\nshould be able to handle it satisfactorily. He\nj s a young man who has made a study of\nState Government. As well as being a per\nsonal appointment for the Governor, we be\nJieve that Mr. Carvel has made\na wise ap\npointment for the administering of the\nstate's affairs with the naming of McDowell,\nMay he continue to make the same calibre of\nThree weeks from today is Christmas\nappointments during his term of office.\nChristmas Three Weeks Off\nve ow g ave p ptxl away, and\nthe holida y s( ason a P'diy closes in upon us.\nJ n wee k\u00bb s i ssue of the Milford Chronicle\nprogressive Merchants from all parts of low\nr and midd1 Delaware are Presenting their\nmessages, and giving a preview in words of\nJUst whac V 0U ma v expect to find in their\nDlaces of business Thesp mpn hnvp nlnrmpf!\nfonv for von Chrfstmas shn\u00ab \u00c4\ny0 U V hrist ma s sho PPers. Ihey have\n\u00abelected Wisely and the merchandise which\nthey are offering is the equal to that to be\nfound in tho lariror citips T^yppot in VQVP\ninstances the average Christmas shotmpr will\nm s mB ces me a era 8 e Christmas shoppei will\nnd n th st res of ower Delaware and near\nb y Maryland as fine merchandise as their'\u00abme\nlarger city merchants have to offer. These\nbusiness interests down state help support'\nthe many charities and other things Of a civ\nic nature that VOU down-staters cherish and\nwant T nnk nvor IVip nflFpvino-c nf\nv aut, .look ovei uie ouermgs^oi ine mer\nChants Who are soliciting your business in\nthis issue of the Chronicle. Why make the\nunnecessary trip to Wilmington or other nor\nthem centers when you can buy the same|\ntrade name merchandise at home? Rend\nuaae name meicnanaise ar nome Lead\nthese advertisements carefully. Make your\nselections Wisely and buy from the men who\nthink enough of their merchandise to pre\nsent it to you for consideration.\nThe PRESENT SITUATION\nWe have inflation this moment. Our Na\ntional debt has risen to $252,000,000,000;\nwe have \"cheap\" dollars which Will purchase\nabout one-half the goods that they would\nfew years ago; we are so entangled with in-!\naffaire that we are sendtag: bil\nlions Of dollars clbioad thclt 3.10 noodod by\nour own countrymen in the United States,\nThe Berlin blockade, the free trade treaties,\nand the failure to make .the United Nations\n\"unite\" can all be traced to the weakness of\nthe Administration and the Congress. They\ndisagreed about everything all through 1948.\nThe United States has to make over a\nlarge part of its fundamental policies. It\nwill be a long and almost endless undertak\nmg because right now we are threatened\nwith another war. We cannot afford risking\nour own independence and our own leader\nship of the affairs of civilized people. That\nmeans that Russia cannot be allowed to de\nstroy the United Nations. In the meantime\nwe do not need to debate with Russia about\nOUR atomic bomb. War is hell, and peace\nful United States is in position to blow hell\nout of Russia. In a tight pinch we could\nuse that little scientific monopoly of ours\nfor (rood purposes.\nNow is the time for the People of the\ntt -a j oa i. j. r\nUnited States to recognize the strength of\nour Government and its honesty of purpose,\nand to remake our great Nation over \u2014as\ngood as it used to be.\nmeans that Russia cannot be allowed to de\nstroy the United Nations. In the meantime\nwe do not need to debate with Russia about\nbusiness except for the influence of the South\nern Democrats,\nwants to shoot Santa Clan\u00ab.\"\nDemocratic Santa Claus has been very good to\nthe farmers who recently have had the most\nTRUMAN AND THE FARMERS\nIt is an old political slogan that \"no one\nCertainly, the\nwonderful years in their history. As Mr. Dewey\ndid not make any substantial promises to the\nfarmers, they felt it wise \"to let well enough\nalone.\" As Mr. Truman is noted for loyalty to\nhis friends, he will oppose any bills which the\nfarmers oppose. Furthermore, the Republi\ncans can expect no help from Southern Demo\ncrats in cutting the profits of the farmers.\nOver a term of years the farmers' profits\nhave not been abnormal. The farmers are en\ntitled to some more good y ears to make up\nduring the i irtie y and y ven before in\ndustry should be judged by the earnings of\nonly a few years. An average of an entire\nicycle should be considered. Surely, on this\nbasis the farmers are entitled to every cent\n(they are getting and to help for some time\nlonger. In fact, for keeping business fairly\ngood the country is very dependent on pros\nperous farmers.\nAnother thing in which the Southern Dem\nocrats can be of no help is in connection with\nStalin's attitude. He is the greatest factor in\nthe business outlook especially in view of de\nTense spending, foreign loans and the Euro\npean Recovery Program,\nmodifier of circumstances to\nTRUMAN AND RUSSIA\nTruman can he a\nsome extent. He\ncannot be the master of destiny whatever his\nrecent campaign,\nability. This foreign situation will be further\ncomplicated hy the political activities of the\nVeterans of World War I and World War II\nwhich activities were largely forgotten in the\nPresident Truman has fighting ability, po\nRtical judgment and vigorous health,\nalso said that he is \"honest;\" but I do not\nunderstand how an honest man who is also\nintelligent could make the promises he did\nin his campaign speeches. He, moreover, ap\npears to lack judgment in recruiting men of\noutstanding ability and tends to \"go off half\nIt is\ncocked\" and spring surprises which may be\nvery dangerous. I doubt if he also fairly bal\nances LOYALTY TO FRIENDS against LOY\nALTY TO THE NATION AS A W HOLE,\nThe real truth is that Mr. Truman doesn't\nknow what he is going to do any more than\nyou who read this article. The forecasts which\ncolumnists and radio commentators made is\nso much wasted time. Mr. Truman\nTHE REAL TRUTH\nwill try to\ncarry out most of his promises, but he does\nnot know which ones he will be able to fulfill\nNo.one else knows. Hence, the only sure\nthing that readers can depend upon is that\nhave two years of great uncertainty ahead.\nWhether for good or evil. I must refer you to\nMr. Stalin's inner thoughts\u2014not necessarily\nto what he says. All of this means that readers\nshould use 1949 for getting out of debt, storing\nup reserves and being prepared for whatever\nwe\nhappens, even though this mav mean \"no\nchange at all.\"\nPOPPING OFF\n\nj\n\nWf\nr- f\u00bb\nMSt\u00e8\u00caS\u00ca\n\nnfp\ngj\nv\nHAW\nV'\n.w .J\n'J**\ni\nSt'\ni\n\n\n5\nr\n\n7\n;a\u00a3\n\n.V\na\nV\nim\n\u00ee r\n.'i\u00ab\nCD\nI\n\nft\n\n3E!\n\u25a0si\n\nmm\nh\n\u00ee\nI\n2\nif V S\n\u00abV\niS\nk\n\u00e9.\nW/\nmi\n?*\u00a3r/cs\n\u00ee\ns\nJ.\ni\nci,\ny\nf\n'v.\nSsil&P\nc |y\n1\ni\n.-\u00bbSV\nK\nDelaware Day Will\n(\u00ab\u00ab\u00abm \u00abm TOe\neach year with the notary flub in\nsponsoring Ihe event.\nloastmaster for the dinner will\nh\" He,man H Hans f P\u00bbver, a\nmember of the Delaware Day Torn\nmission. He will he assisted by E.\nBertram Blunt, club \u201eresident. V.\nHanson said the meeting will be\neld in v the htgh sch0Gl to accomo\nQale (he many euests expected\nWomen win be \u201eresen V tor the first\nlhe \u2022'tS*.\u2122 111 lhe 8tatc s\n\u00c4'.h\u00c4 S\u00c4Tcto\u00dc;\nplan to engage sneakers tor the im!\ncasion.\nmnv- -enlistments\ni\nj x rocm\u00fciation\n\nWHEREAS, on December 7 17S7\nI)elawar e became the first state to\nratlfy ,he Federal Constitution;\nand\nj WHEREAS, by resolution of the\nGeneral Assembly of the State of\nI Delaware, approved on the twenty\ni A i D\n\u00c4*\ning attention to the importance and\nsi c an ^r 0 is historical event;\nj W Bacon Gmlrno\u00ee^' the State o'\nDelaware, do hereby designate\na'Tuesday, December 7. ms, as\nDelaware day\npart Delaware played in the found\"\nins of the Republic by the prompt\nratification of the Federal consti\nd i h tbemsel\npreservation of ou\u00ef 25 and its\nway of life, i further suggest that\n,,f our s,a, an(J Nation he\nd Jf p,ayed a, d th at a11 8cb P o1\nZZT\ncommemoration of this date in his\ntor >V\nTES'IIMONV WHEREOF I\nSf a lto r nf \u00b0h/p\u00ab\u201entn\nset mv hand and the Great seal of\nthe State of Delaware has been\nh ,n a to a ffi e